<span class="accent-letter-defi"> <ul style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"> <li><b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b> is pronounced <i>oo</i>, as in gl<b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>e, J<b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>ne, f<b style="color: blue;"><u>oo</u></b>d </li> <li>Spanish examples: <b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>no [one] c<b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>c<b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>r<b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>cho [cone] <b style="color: blue;"><u>u</u></b>niversidad [university]</li> <ul> <li><b>Jaw</b> – The jaw drops slightly.</li> <li><b>Lips</b> – The lips part slightly and push outward, making a tense, small circle.</li> <li><b>Tongue</b> - The back of the tongue is raised to a high position and the sides may touch the top teeth at the back of the mouth.</li> <li><b>Airflow</b> - Spanish vowels are generally shorter in duration than their English counterpart. The air produced passes from the lungs to the vocal tract and out of the mouth without any stops.</li> </ul> </ul> </span> </span> </span>